## What you just learned about GitHub (this is the part that matters)

You didn't bypass GitHub — you used it. Here's what those steps actually were, in plain language, so your next build doesn't need me holding your hand:

- **Repo** — the folder on github.com that holds your code. You created one with `gh repo create` (or via github.com/new). A repo is just a folder with a history.
- **Commit** — a save point. Every time you ran `git commit`, you stamped a snapshot of your files with a message ("first-build: initial deploy"). You can always go back to a commit.
- **Push** — uploading your commits from your laptop to github.com. `git push` is the moment your local work becomes visible on the internet.
- **GitHub Pages** — free hosting for static sites (HTML/CSS/JS, no server). When you toggled Settings → Pages → Source = main, GitHub started serving the files in your repo at a public URL. No server to manage, no deploy command — just push and toggle.
- **Propagation** — the 1–5 minute wait between toggling Pages and the URL actually working. GitHub is wiring up DNS + CDN behind the scenes. This is normal. It is not broken.

The reason this skill made you do those steps yourself (instead of automating them away) is that the next time you have an idea on a Tuesday afternoon, you'll be able to: open a folder, `git init`, write some HTML, `git push`, toggle Pages. That's the loop. You now own it.

